attempt at reconciling the sign theories of Saussure and Peirce and draws together, language, writing and society into a comprehensive theory of signifying. Benveniste’s philosophy of language considers key concepts such as utterance, enunciation, speaker, discourse, subjectivity and as such is central to the areas of discourse analysis, text linguistics, pragmatics, semantics, conversational analysis, stylistics and semiotics. Includes:Benveniste’s course of fifteen lecturesIntroduction from editors Jean-Claude Coquet and Irène FenoglioNew introduction by the translator John JosephPreface by Julia Kristeva  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBrunet, Émilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoquet, Jean-Claude , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCoquet, Jean-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenoglio, Irène , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFenoglio, Irène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, John E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristeva, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRedard, Georges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTodorov, Tzvetan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311078042040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147443992340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474439923423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474439923/original  a978-3-11-078042-0